have a heart-shaped appearance with a deep fundal cleft and two distinct horns partially fused at the isthmus. The placenta is located in the right horn.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological basis of the uterine abnormality described in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete septation of a single uterine cavity","Incomplete fusion of m\u00fcllerian ducts","Failed regression of mesonephric ducts","Complete failure of m\u00fcllerian duct formation","Failed canalization of vaginal plate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a bicornuate uterus which results from \u003Cstrong\u003Eincomplete fusion of m\u00fcllerian ducts\u003C/strong\u003E during weeks 6-11 of embryological development. The partial fusion at the isthmus with two distinct horns is characteristic of this anomaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete failure of m\u00fcllerian duct formation\u003C/strong\u003E would result in uterine agenesis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailed regression of mesonephric ducts\u003C/strong\u003E affects male rather than female development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete septation of a single uterine cavity\u003C/strong\u003E describes a septate uterus which has a normal external appearance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailed canalization of vaginal plate\u003C/strong\u003E would affect vaginal rather than uterine development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe m\u00fcllerian ducts normally fuse in the midline to form the uterus, cervix and upper third of the vagina. Incomplete fusion results in various degrees of uterine duplication, with bicornuate uterus being a common variant. This anomaly is associated with adverse pregnancy outcomes including preterm labour and malpresentation. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A bicornuate uterus forms when there is incomplete fusion of the m\u00fcllerian ducts during embryological development.","The m\u00fcllerian (paramesonephric) ducts normally fuse between weeks 6-11 of embryological development to form the uterus, cervix and upper vagina.","Bicornuate uterus is associated with increased risk of preterm labour, breech presentation, and caesarean delivery."],"references":["Akhtar MA, Saravelos SH, Li TC, Jayaprakasan K; on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Reproductive implications and management of congenital uterine anomalies. Scientific Impact Paper No. 62. BJOG. 2019 Nov 20; DOI: 10.1111/1471-0528.15968.","Jayaprakasan K, Ojha K. Diagnosis of Congenital Uterine Abnormalities: Practical Considerations. J Clin Med. 2022 Feb 25;11(5):1251. doi: 10.3390/jcm11051251. PMID: 35268343; PMCID: PMC8911320."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77288"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16912"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77288"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T16:11:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T16:11:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9602"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94202"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":